+# Solution: Support ORDER BY in SQLite aggregate functions (PR #38344)
+
+## Root Cause
+
+SQLite 3.44.0 (released October 2023) added support for an `ORDER BY` clause inside aggregate function calls, e.g. `group_concat(x, sep ORDER BY x ASC)`. The EF Core SQLite provider was unaware of this capability: `SqliteStringAggregateMethodTranslator` unconditionally returned `null` (refusing translation) whenever `source.Orderings.Count > 0`, forcing client-side evaluation and silently producing wrong or unordered results for LINQ queries like:
+
+```csharp
+.GroupBy(c => c.Int)
+.Select(g => new { Key = g.Key, Strings = string.Join("|", g.OrderByDescending(e => e.Id).Select(e => e.String)) })
+```
+
+## Change Description
+
+### New expression type
+**`src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/SqlExpressions/SqliteAggregateFunctionExpression.cs`** (new file)
+
+A new `SqliteAggregateFunctionExpression : SqlExpression` that carries a function name, arguments, and a list of `OrderingExpression`s. This mirrors `SqlServerAggregateFunctionExpression` but targets the SQLite `func(args ORDER BY ...)` syntax instead of SQL Server's `WITHIN GROUP (ORDER BY ...)`.
+
+### Translator update
+**`src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/Translators/SqliteStringAggregateMethodTranslator.cs`**
+
+Removed the early `return null` guard when `source.Orderings.Count > 0`. When orderings are present, the translator now produces a `SqliteAggregateFunctionExpression`; otherwise it continues to produce a plain `SqlFunctionExpression` (no behaviour change for the no-ordering path).
+
+### SQL generation
+**`src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/SqliteQuerySqlGenerator.cs`**
+
+Added `VisitSqliteAggregateFunction` that emits `name(arg1, arg2 ORDER BY col1 ASC, col2 DESC)`. The new case is dispatched from `VisitExtension`.
+
+### Nullability processor
+**`src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/SqliteSqlNullabilityProcessor.cs`**
+
+Added `VisitSqliteAggregateFunction` that visits arguments and orderings, forwarding nullability from `IsNullable`, matching the pattern used by `SqlServerSqlNullabilityProcessor`.
+
+### Type mapping factory
+**`src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/SqliteSqlExpressionFactory.cs`**
+
+Added a `SqliteAggregateFunctionExpression` arm to `ApplyTypeMapping` that delegates to the expression's own `ApplyTypeMapping` method, consistent with how SQL Server handles its aggregate expression.
+
+### Test update
+**`test/EFCore.Sqlite.FunctionalTests/Query/Translations/StringTranslationsSqliteTest.cs`**
+
+Updated `Join_with_ordering` test: removed the "does client evaluation" comment and replaced the client-eval SQL with the expected server-side SQL:
+```sql
+SELECT "b"."Int" AS "Key", COALESCE(group_concat("b"."String", '|' ORDER BY "b"."Id" DESC), '') AS "Strings"
+FROM "BasicTypesEntities" AS "b"
+GROUP BY "b"."Int"
+```
+
+## Files Edited
+
+| File | Change |
+|------|--------|
+| `src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/SqlExpressions/SqliteAggregateFunctionExpression.cs` | **New** — expression node for aggregate functions with ORDER BY |
+| `src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/Translators/SqliteStringAggregateMethodTranslator.cs` | Use `SqliteAggregateFunctionExpression` when orderings are present |
+| `src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/SqliteQuerySqlGenerator.cs` | Emit `func(args ORDER BY ...)` SQL |
+| `src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/SqliteSqlNullabilityProcessor.cs` | Visit new expression type |
+| `src/EFCore.Sqlite.Core/Query/Internal/SqliteSqlExpressionFactory.cs` | Handle type mapping for new expression |
+| `test/EFCore.Sqlite.FunctionalTests/Query/Translations/StringTranslationsSqliteTest.cs` | Update `Join_with_ordering` expected SQL |
